{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:42:58.246561", "event": "llm_start", "prompts": ["System: You are an expert network engineer.\nYour task is to submit the final solution for this network problem based on the diagnosis reported provided.\nCarefully review the diagnosis results and ensure that your submission is accurate and complete.\nYou must strictly follow the submission format and call the submit() tool to submit your solution.\nHuman: Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnostic report — multi-tier Clos (EBGP) lab\n\nSummary / overall health\n- Control plane (BGP) appears largely healthy and converged: all routers have BGP entries for the two host subnets (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) and next-hops look consistent with the topology.\n- Data-plane/forwarding is broken for host-to-host traffic: pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 cannot reach each other (100% packet loss observed).\n- Fault is localized to leaf_router_0_0. The root cause is a kernel-installed blackhole/unreachable route for 10.0.0.0/24 on leaf_router_0_0 that is preventing delivery of packets for that subnet.\n\nObserved symptoms and tests performed\n1. End-host reachability test (global view)\n   - get_reachability: pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 4 sent, 0 received, 100% loss.\n\n2. Interface / IP configuration (hosts and routers)\n   - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0)\n   - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1)\n   - leaf_router_0_0:\n     - eth2: 10.0.0.1/24 (connected to pc_0_0)\n     - eth0: 172.16.0.5/31 (to spine_router_0_0)\n     - eth1: 172.16.0.9/31 (to spine_router_0_1)\n   - leaf_router_0_1:\n     - eth2: 10.0.1.1/24 (connected to pc_0_1)\n     - inter-router /31s consistent with topology\n   - spine and super-spine interfaces have expected /31s and are UP.\n\n3. BGP tables (control-plane)\n   - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200): BGP shows 10.0.0.0/24 as locally originated (next-hop 0.0.0.0), and 10.0.1.0/24 learned from spine(s).\n   - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201), spines (AS 65100 / 65101) and super-spine (AS 65000) all show both /24 networks in their BGP tables with expected next-hops. Path attributes look consistent — no missing prefixes.\n\n4. Connectivity tests from routers\n   - ping from leaf_router_0_0 to pc_0_1: 3 packets transmitted, 0 received, 100% loss (leaf_router_0_0 cannot reach other host).\n   - ping from pc_0_1 to pc_0_0: 3 transmitted, 0 received, 100% loss.\n\n5. Routing/FIB on leaf_router_0_0 (critical evidence)\n   - ip -d route and show ip route on leaf_router_0_0 show:\n     - A kernel route (K) entry: \"K * 10.0.0.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\"\n     - Also present: \"C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth2\"\n     - ip -d route lists \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24 proto boot scope global\" before the local entries.\n   - In short: leaf_router_0_0 has a blackhole/unreachable route for its own LAN prefix 10.0.0.0/24 installed in the kernel/RIB and that blackhole is taking effect.\n\nAnalysis / localization\n- Because BGP is advertising both /24s correctly and next-hops across spines and super-spine appear consistent, the control plane is not the immediate problem.\n- Packets from pc_0_1 follow the normal path to leaf_router_0_0 (through spine), but when leaf_router_0_0 receives packets for 10.0.0.0/24 they are matched by the kernel blackhole/unreachable route and dropped instead of being delivered out eth2 to pc_0_0.\n- The presence of both a blackhole (K) route and a connected (C) route for the same prefix on leaf_router_0_0 indicates the forwarding plane is configured/installed incorrectly for that prefix on that router. This is the direct cause of the observed end-to-end connectivity failure.\n\nRoot cause\n- A blackhole/unreachable kernel route for 10.0.0.0/24 exists on leaf_router_0_0 and is taking precedence in the FIB, causing packets destined to the 10.0.0.0/24 network to be dropped instead of forwarded to the local interface (eth2). This misinstalled/unexpected kernel route is the root cause of host-to-host connectivity failure.\n\nImpact\n- pc_0_0 is unreachable from other hosts (pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1/spines), and traffic destined for 10.0.0.0/24 arriving at leaf_router_0_0 will be dropped.\n- BGP control-plane visibility remains intact — other routers believe they can reach the 10.0.0.0/24 network and forward traffic toward leaf_router_0_0, but the forwarding plane on leaf_router_0_0 prevents delivery.\n\nEvidence (representative lines)\n- Reachability: pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 100% loss\n- leaf_router_0_0 show ip route:\n  - \"K * 10.0.0.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole)\"\n  - \"C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth2\"\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip -d route:\n  - \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24 proto boot scope global\"\n  - local 10.0.0.1 dev eth2 table local ...\n\nConfidence\n- High: the blackhole/unreachable route on leaf_router_0_0 is directly observable in the kernel route table and explains the exact symptom (packets dropped for 10.0.0.0/24). BGP and interface states corroborate that forwarding on that router is the broken piece.\n\nNotes (no remediation included)\n- The report deliberately does not propose remediation steps (per request). If you want, I can next (on request) identify the likely configuration command or FRR behavior that installed the blackhole route and show exact configuration outputs (FRR running-config) to further pinpoint the misconfiguration., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
